of higher education's political economy. Instead, service, silent and invisible, coexists with the formal "official" economy of many institutions, just as women's unrecognized domestic labor props up the formal, official economies of countries the world over. Over Ten Million Served explores what academic service is and investigates why this labor is often not acknowledged as "labor" by administrators or even by faculty themselves, but is instead relegated to a gendered form of institutional caregiving. By analyzing the actual labor of service, particularly for women and racial, ethnic, and sexual minorities, contributors expose the hidden economy of institutional service, challenging the feminization of service labor in the academy for both female and male academic laborers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aFeminism and higher educationzUnited States. 0aSex discrimination in higher educationzUnited States. 0aWomen college teachersxProfessional relationshipszUnited States. 0aWomen college teachersxWorkloadzUnited States. 4aBusiness and Economics : Labor Economics. 4aEducation : Higher Education. 4aEducation : Social Context of Education. 4aGender and Sexuality : Feminist. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh1 aAdolph, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBass, Margaret Kent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBousquet, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurgan, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChancy, Myriam J. A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristensen, Kirsten M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClausen, Jeanette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.go